'''Peak capitalism''' is a term used in recent academic literature to describe a situation in which [[capitalism]] can no longer survive. The phrase is based on the concept of [[peak oil]] and suggests that a capitalist system in a [[postmodern]] world can no longer survive, given that the international system depends entirely upon non-renewable resources to reproduce society.<ref>http://rdwolff.com/content/peak-oil-and-peak-capitalism</ref><ref>http://endofcapitalism.com/category/collapse/</ref><ref>http://members.optusnet.com.au/~lionelorford/Peak%20Capitalism%20exec%20summary.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.springerlink.com/content/v70637451h2upwj6/ | doi=10.1007/0-306-48082-4_17 | title=Schumpeter and the Crisis of the Tax State | journal=The European Heritage in Economics and the Social Sciences | pages=337–351 | last1 = Schmidt | first1 = Karl-Heinz}}</ref><ref>Schmidt, Karl-Heinz 2003, 'Schumpeter and the Crisis of the Tax State', The European Heritage in Economics and the Social Sciences, 2003, Volume 1, pages 337–351</ref>

